# Conditional Statements üîÄ

Run code only if a condition is true.

```javascript
if (hour < 18) {
  greeting = "Good day";
} else {
  greeting = "Good evening";
}
```

## Else If

```javascript
if (time < 10) {
  greeting = "Good morning";
} else if (time < 20) {
  greeting = "Good day";
} else {
  greeting = "Good evening";
}
```

# Switch Statement üö¶

Selects one of many code blocks to execute. Cleaner than many `else if`s.

```javascript
switch (new Date().getDay()) {
  case 0:
    day = "Sunday";
    break;
  case 1:
    day = "Monday";
    break;
  default:
    day = "Unknown";
}
```

> ‚ö†Ô∏è **Important:** Don't forget `break`, or it will fall through to the next case!

# The For Loop üîÑ

Repeats a block of code a specified number of times.

Syntax: `for (initialization; condition; increment)`

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  console.log("Number: " + i);
}
// Beeps: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4
```

# While Loop üîÅ

Loops through a block of code as long as a specified condition is true.

```javascript
let i = 0;
while (i < 10) {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}
```

> ‚ö†Ô∏è **Warning:** If you forget to increment `i`, you'll get an infinite loop and crash your browser!

# Do...While Loop ‚Ü©Ô∏è

A variant of the while loop. It **always** executes the code block once, before checking the condition.

```javascript
let i = 0;
do {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
} while (i < 5);
```

# Modern Loops üÜï

## For...In
Loops through the **properties** (keys) of an object.
```javascript
for (let key in person) {
  console.log(key);
}
```

## For...Of
Loops through the **values** of an iterable (Array, String, etc.).
```javascript
let cars = ["BMW", "Volvo", "Mini"];
for (let car of cars) {
  console.log(car);
}
```
Often preferred over standard `for` loop for arrays.

# Break and Continue üõë

## Break
Jumps out of a loop entirely.

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  if (i === 3) { break; }
  console.log(i);
}
// Prints 0, 1, 2
```

## Continue
Jumps over one iteration in the loop.

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  if (i === 3) { continue; }
  console.log(i);
}
// Prints 0, 1, 2, 4
```
